@page "/enigma-multiplayer"

<SeoHead Title="Enigma Multiplayer | Co-op Maze Sessions and Shared Puzzle Runs"
         Description="Learn how Enigma multiplayer works, from invites and ready checks to synchronized room movement, shared puzzle progress, and co-op completion."
         OpenGraphType="article"
         SchemaType="Article"
         Keywords="Enigma multiplayer, co-op maze game, shared puzzle runs, cooperative puzzle maze" />

<div class="content seo-page-shell">
    <section class="panel seo-page-hero">
        <span class="profile-kicker">Co-op</span>
        <h1>Enigma Multiplayer</h1>
        <p>Enigma multiplayer is designed for two-player co-op. One player creates a session, invites a friend, and both players enter the same maze once they are ready.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="panel seo-page-section">
        <h2>Session Flow</h2>
        <h3>Invite and Join</h3>
        <p>The owner creates a co-op session and invites one friend. The invited player can join through the co-op lobby.</p>
        <h3>Ready Check</h3>
        <p>Both players must be present and ready before the shared maze begins.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="panel seo-page-section">
        <h2>Shared Run Rules</h2>
        <h3>Synchronized Movement</h3>
        <p>Both players move through the same room sequence. Room transitions are synchronized and rely on shared session state.</p>
        <h3>Shared Progress</h3>
        <p>Puzzle completion, room rewards, and finish conditions all operate at the session level rather than as two separate solo runs.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="panel seo-page-section">
        <h2>Completion and Loss</h2>
        <h3>Finish Rules</h3>
        <p>Co-op completion requires both players to satisfy the finish conditions together.</p>
        <h3>Abandoning the Session</h3>
        <p>If one player leaves the real co-op game, the session is abandoned and the run is lost for the team.</p>
    </section>
</div>
